Namaste friends,
=C2=A0
Someone with psychiatric problems may expereience w=
hat sounds like a Kundalini rise, but it may or may not be one.
=C2=A0
It m=
ust be conceded though that Kundalini spontaneously rising through various =
nadis without one having gone through proper preparation in this life (i.e.=
 fine-tuning of one's attitude and development of detachment) CAN create ha=
voc!
=C2=A0
One may wonder how Kundalini may spontaneously rise in a layman=
 with no sadhana, while many serious sadhakas may not experience it.
=C2=A0=

Firstly, Kundalini rise is NOT an achievement. It is just A SMALL STEP in =
overcoming one's current limited identity.
=C2=A0
Let me give an analogy. O=
ne wanting to move from one's small dilapidated house (this
 body-mind comp=
lex) to a huge palace (realized Self) may first construct the palace over t=
ime and move into it when it is COMPLETE. Alternately, if one occasionally =
goes and stays in the palace still under construction (analogy for out of b=
ody experiences due to Kundalini rise), is it an achievement? In fact, it c=
omes with risks. The former approach is safer and one loses nothing in it. =
Similarly, one can progress towards complete Self-realization without any o=
ut of body experiences. These are not my word's, but Maharshi Vasishtha's w=
ords to Lord Rama.
=C2=A0
Secondly, one does not get something without want=
ing it and putting sufficient effort towards it. One may have deeply desire=
d a Kundalini rise in a previous life and may have put enough effort. As a =
result, one may be getting it now. But one may be unprepared (and ironicall=
y may not even want it!) when it comes in this life.
=C2=A0
As you do sadha=
na, try not to fancy too many specific desires. Nature has a delay mechanis=
m in granting your desires (because of constraints on what Nature can give =
you right now, arising from YOUR
 OWN previous actions). So Nature sometime=
s gives you what you want LATE, when you no longer want it or want somethin=
g else. For example, one may pray for great wealth one's whole life and be =
born as a rich but very sick man in next life. One may not enjoy that wealt=
h and pray whole life for health. In the life after that, one may be very h=
ealthy, but not have any knowledge or money. In another 
case, one may deep=
ly desire to act in a famous film. One may be reborn 
as a tiger or a dog a=
nd act in a famous film, but not really enjoy that 
experience. Basically, =
people keep going in circles through various lives, always "seeking" someth=
ing they are "missing".
=C2=A0
Anyway, coming back to Kundalini, if one dee=
ply desires an out of body experience given by a rising Kundalini and one's=
 previous karmas constrain one from having it in THIS life, one may be born=
 in next life with this specific desire destined to fructify (if there is e=
nough karmik force behind it).
=C2=A0
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=
=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
 *
=C2=A0
Kundalini rise=
 is not necessarily scary or painful, if one is well-prepared in terms of a=
ttitude and detachment.
=C2=A0
Once I saw a chipmunk glued to a mouse trap.=
 I went to free it and it panicked so badly and started to shake violently.=
 I went to save it from a certain slow death and it was scared that I would=
 kill it!
=C2=A0
We are like that chipmunk, glued to the mouse trap called =
this body-mind complex and scared of being rescued from a certain slow deat=
h!
=C2=A0
If our ideas about who we are (viz this current body-mind complex=
) are incorrect and if we are this "infinite Self" as shastras say, won't a=
 complete realization of that at some stage involve stepping out of this bo=
dy-mind complex, without being scared?
=C2=A0
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=
=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *
=C2=A0
Kundal=
ini rise after most undesirable conditioning is overcome, is far better tha=
n Kundalini rise forced when some really undesirable conditioning is still =
left in one's system.
=C2=A0
When one transcends one problematic notion abo=
ut who one is and what one needs, another notion that lay buried deeper in =
consciousness may spring to the surface and torment one. If one overcomes t=
he notion "I am the body", there may be another notion in one's body-mind c=
omplex that one's awareness clings on to (e.g. a great doctor, a great lead=
er, a great scholar, a great saint etc). As an extreme example, if one pers=
on had a hidden deep desire to be a great soul who rescues the world, he ma=
y fancy that he is a re-incarnated X or Y who will rescue the world now. Wh=
en one's self-awareness (i.e. Kundalini!) deeply clings to any such notion,=
 it can cause havoc. The person may show some signs of progress and yet rem=
ain in ignorance and get stuck badly.
=C2=A0
An awakened Kundalini in a sys=
tem with undesirable conditioning may accentuate one's weaknesses and wrong=
 notions heavily and cause serious psychiatric and spiritual problems.
=C2=
=A0
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=
=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *
=C2=A0
The best approach I recommend is to NOT think i=
n terms of Kundalini and its rise. Just do sadhana, overcome your
 weakness=
es and improve your detachment over time. Again, I want to emphasize that d=
etachment is not disgust or distaste for life/things/people around you. Dis=
gust is the other side of coin of attachment. It is a negative attachment.
=
=C2=A0

Don't worry about 
whether your Kundalini rises or not. Worry about=
 whether you are able to resist 6 internal enemies (shadripus) and 8 bondag=
es (ashta pashas) or 
not. If your ability to resist them is increasing, yo=
u are making progress. EVEN IF your Kundalini is fast asleep, you are still=
 making progress. When you completely overcome them, Kundalini (your self-a=
wareness) 
will automatically ascend to the top and meet Her Lord (true Sel=
f).
=C2=A0
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=
=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *
=C2=A0
One word on surrendering to a personal de=
ity. Though true surrender is helpful, most people do not have it. They sim=
ply do business with god. Though people may be offended by my words, this i=
s the plain and bare fact.
=C2=A0
"I want X, I will pray to you and please =
give it to me", "I am scared of Kundalini rise, I will pray to you and plea=
se protect me" - all this is just a business deal. There is something you w=
ant and you ask god for it. True surrender has no place for agendas, desire=
s, demands or expectations. True surrender is losing oneself in one's fasci=
nation for the qualities of Lord. True surrender is accepting anything Lord=
 throws one's way (whether it is pleasurable or highly painful) as Lord's p=
rasad and accepting it gratefully. True surrender is thinking of Lord with =
fascination and pleasure, even in the face of (and during) Death.
=C2=A0
If=
 one without true surrender and with many desires and wrong notions experie=
nces a Kundalini rise, one may still be trapped, despite thinking of a pers=
onal god. It is not that god does not want to "protect" one as said below. =
It is not about protecting or endangering. If you go back to my "chipmunk g=
lued to mouse trap" example above, I was trying to protect it, but it was s=
cared. Similarly, one's conditioning makes one *run away* from God's protec=
tion! God's protection may seem to a conditioned mind like grave danger tha=
t one should run away from!
=C2=A0
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=
=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *
=C2=A0
Whether through th=
e path of wisdom or surrender, develop dispassion and detachment. Realize t=
hat all this is temporary and can be taken away anytime. Enjoy it while you=
 have and keep doing your best, but be prepared to lose everything anytime.=
 Only detachment and a very light mental conditioning (very light desires, =
dislikes etc) can protect one as one's Kundalini rises to meet True Self. H=
eavy conditioning and impurities in one's nadis will distract rising Kundal=
ini (self-awareness) and stop Her from meeting True Self.
=C2=A0
The real k=
ey is how light your conditioning is.
=C2=A0
Best regards,
Narasimha
