>>Dear all, Just wanted to warn people of=
 kundalini syndrome based on my recent experience of a patient of mine. I a=
m doing a psychiatry job at present, and have been involved in the care of =
someone who seems to think she has had a spontaneous awakening of their kun=
dalini since childhood. This has involved out-of-body experiences and surge=
s of energy in the body. She is not of Indian origin and had never heard of=
 kundalini until her symptoms started and she searched for an explanation. =
We have not been able to find anything physically wrong with her (all tests=
 normal)- so it might be that this is due to deranged kundalini. Many peopl=
e we call mentally ill describe themselves as having a spiritual crisis, or=
 unwanted spontaneous kundalini awakening- this has triggered interest and =
research into this topic in mainstream psychiatry. Unfortunately these pati=
ents are not well-understood by western medicine, and as we have no treatme=
nts for deranged kundalini,
 we struggle to help them. Many yogis try to fo=
rcibly waken the kundalini. My experience with this lady confirmed my feeli=
ng that kundalini should not be forcibly wakened. This woman wants to kill =
herself at times because the suffering from the deranged energy is so bad. =
She feels it will consume her, and it is something she cannot escape from. =
I wondered what solution there could be to her problem. The logical one was=
 to pray to the Divine Mother, who manifests as the kundalini to relieve th=
e suffering of this woman- and either cure her, or give her the strength to=
 bear this. May I request that the good samaritans among you pray for her, =
and for others like her (whom we may not know of)- their suffering really i=
s pitiable. And let us be careful in our sadhana so as not to end up in thi=
s situation ourselves. Perhaps this is why the bhakti marga is the safest. =
It is perhaps safest to say "let me be your instrument" and leave the kunda=
lini rising bit to
 God's will. Om Dum Durgayai Namaha Aparna 
