<div>Dear all, Just wanted to warn people =
of kundalini syndrome based on my recent experience of a patient of mine. I=
 am doing a psychiatry job at present, and have been involved in the care o=
f someone who seems to think she has had a spontaneous awakening of their k=
undalini since childhood. This has involved out-of-body experiences and sur=
ges of energy in the body. She is not of Indian origin and had never heard =
of kundalini until her symptoms started and she searched for an explanation=
. We have not been able to find anything physically wrong with her (all tes=
ts normal)- so it might be that this is due to deranged kundalini. Many peo=
ple we call mentally ill describe themselves as having a spiritual crisis, =
or unwanted spontaneous kundalini awakening- this has triggered interest an=
d research into this topic in mainstream psychiatry. Unfortunately these pa=
tients are not well-understood by western medicine, and as we have no treat=
ments
 for deranged kundalini, we struggle to help them. Many yogis try to =
forcibly waken the kundalini. My experience with this lady confirmed my fee=
ling that kundalini should not be forcibly wakened. This woman wants to kil=
l herself at times because the suffering from the deranged energy is so bad=
. She feels it will consume her, and it is something she cannot escape from=
. I wondered what solution there could be to her problem. The logical one w=
as to pray to the Divine Mother, who manifests as the kundalini to relieve =
the suffering of this woman- and either cure her, or give her the strength =
to bear this. May I request that the good samaritans among you pray for her=
, and for others like her (whom we may not know of)- their suffering really=
 is pitiable. And let us be careful in our sadhana so as not to end up in t=
his situation ourselves. Perhaps this is why the bhakti marga is the safest=
. It is perhaps safest to say "let me be your
 instrument" and leave the ku=
ndalini rising bit to God's will. Om Dum Durgayai Namaha Aparna </div></div=
